# **6. Why does this work?**

The queue always stores only the requests within the last **3000 milliseconds**.

When a new request arrives:

* Add it to the rear.
* Remove all outdated requests from the front.

Since requests come in increasing order of time, once a request is removed, it will never be needed again.

Each request is:

* added once
* removed once

So the algorithm is very efficient.

---

# **7. Java Code**

```java
class RecentCounter {

    Queue<Integer> queue;

    public RecentCounter() {
        queue = new LinkedList<>();
    }

    public int ping(int t) {

        queue.offer(t);

        while (queue.peek() < t - 3000) {
            queue.poll();
        }

        return queue.size();
    }
}
```

> **Safer version (recommended):**

```java
class RecentCounter {

    Queue<Integer> queue;

    public RecentCounter() {
        queue = new LinkedList<>();
    }

    public int ping(int t) {

        queue.offer(t);

        while (!queue.isEmpty() && queue.peek() < t - 3000) {
            queue.poll();
        }

        return queue.size();
    }
}
```

---

# **8. Time Complexity**

Each request is inserted once and removed at most once.

For `n` calls:

```text
O(n)
```

Amortized time per `ping()`:

```text
O(1)
```

---

# **9. Space Complexity**

The queue stores only the recent requests (at most all requests in the last 3000 ms).

Worst case:

```text
O(n)
```

---

# **10. Important Interview Note**

This is a classic **Sliding Window using a Queue**.

The queue always represents the current window:

```text
[t - 3000, t]
```

Whenever a new request arrives:

* Enqueue it.
* Dequeue all outdated requests.
* The queue size is the answer.

Unlike array-based sliding window problems, we don't use two pointers because the data arrives **online** (one request at a time). A queue naturally maintains the moving window.

---

# **11. One-line Note for Interviews**

**Use a Queue to maintain all requests within the last 3000 milliseconds. Enqueue the current request, dequeue all requests older than `t - 3000`, and return the queue size.** 🚀
